@startuml ManagerLifecycleStateMachine
' https://plantuml.com/state-diagram
' Narrative: lib/everest/framework/src/manager.hpp
' Transitions / timeouts: lib/everest/framework/src/manager.cpp
'
' Transition text is on the arrows (line breaks via backslash-n in labels). See manager.hpp for full narrative.
' Where arrows use -[#RRGGBB]->, the **first line** of the label uses <color:#RRGGBB>…</color> (closed **before** the first \n) so tint matches stroke; continuation lines use default label color (PlantUML creole).
' Color rule: that # is the **source** state's fill (same hex as on `state Name #hex` / composite `as Alias #hex`), not a separate palette.
' State fills are mid/dark saturation so those same hexes read clearly as arrow stroke and creole label color on the light page background.
' Exception: `[*] --> Idle` has no source state, so it keeps the diagram default (no custom stroke).
' Color key: see legend at end of diagram.
' (Avoid ortho here: it often detaches labels from the correct arrow in previews.)
'
' Line breaks: \n works in many previews on transition labels; inside note/end note blocks it
' often prints literally. For notes, break lines by pressing Enter in the source (short lines).
'
' G_DRAIN is the PlantUML alias for composite state "Shutdown / drain" (see "as G_DRAIN" below).
' G_DRAIN --> ShutdownFinalizing: one composite transition when all module PIDs are gone.
' Optional on newer PlantUML only:
' !theme cerulean-outline
' !pragma layout smetana

top to bottom direction

' skinparam linetype ortho
skinparam backgroundColor #F8FAFC
skinparam defaultFontName Verdana
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam ArrowThickness 1.3
skinparam roundcorner 12
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam nodesep 30
skinparam ranksep 40
skinparam state {
  BorderColor #0f172a
  FontColor #f8fafc
  FontStyle bold
  FontSize 11
}
skinparam note {
  BackgroundColor #FFFBEB
  BorderColor #D97706
  FontColor #422006
  FontSize 10
}
skinparam legend {
  BackgroundColor #F1F5F9
  BorderColor #94A3B8
  FontSize 9
}

scale max 1100 width

title EVerest manager - ManagerState, events, ShutdownCause

hide empty description

state "Startup" as G_BOOT #6366f1 {
  state Idle #64748b
  state Initializing #818cf8
  state StartingModules #4f46e5
  state Running #3730a3

  [*] --> Idle : construct
  Idle -[#64748b]-> Initializing : <color:#64748b>run()</color>
  Initializing -[#818cf8]-> StartingModules : <color:#818cf8>handle_start_modules(), spawn,</color>\nMQTT ready handlers
  StartingModules -[#4f46e5]-> Running : <color:#4f46e5>MQTT all non-ignored modules ready</color>
}

state "Shutdown / drain" as G_DRAIN #d97706 {
  state ShutdownRequested #ca8a04
  state CrashShutdownInProgress #ea580c
  state RestartRequested #c2410c
  state ForceTerminating #9a3412

  ShutdownRequested -[#ca8a04]-> ForceTerminating : <color:#ca8a04>ShutdownRequested to ForceTerminating</color>\ntimer exceeds SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT_MS
  CrashShutdownInProgress -[#ea580c]-> ForceTerminating : <color:#ea580c>CrashShutdownInProgress to ForceTerminating</color>\ntimer exceeds SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT_MS
  RestartRequested -[#c2410c]-> ForceTerminating : <color:#c2410c>RestartRequested to ForceTerminating</color>\ntimer exceeds SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT_MS
}

state "Finalize" as G_END #059669 {
  state ShutdownFinalizing #047857
  state Exiting #dc2626

  ShutdownFinalizing -[#047857]-> Exiting : <color:#047857>Finish after SIGINT shutdown</color>\n sigint_received_: cleanup, EXIT_SUCCESS\n(unclean module exits log warning, still success)
  Exiting -[#dc2626]-> [*] : <color:#dc2626>process exit</color>
}

'--- Cross-region transitions: stroke/label # = **source** state fill (see state declarations above)---

Running -[#3730a3]-> ShutdownRequested : <color:#3730a3>Running to ShutdownRequested:</color>\n first SIGINT/SIGTERM,\n Normal cause,\n MQTT shutdown published
StartingModules -[#4f46e5]-> ShutdownRequested : <color:#4f46e5>first SIGINT/SIGTERM,</color>\nNormal cause,\nMQTT shutdown published

Running -[#3730a3]-> CrashShutdownInProgress : <color:#3730a3>Running to CrashShutdownInProgress:</color>\n waitpid module exit,\n Crash cause
StartingModules -[#4f46e5]-> CrashShutdownInProgress : <color:#4f46e5>waitpid module exit,</color>\nCrash cause

Running -[#3730a3]-> RestartRequested : <color:#3730a3>Running to RestartRequested:</color>\nIPC restart_modules,\n Restart cause
StartingModules -[#4f46e5]-> RestartRequested : <color:#4f46e5>IPC restart_modules,</color>\nRestart cause

G_DRAIN -[#d97706]-> ShutdownFinalizing : <color:#d97706>all module PIDs gone</color>\n(drain or after SIGTERM/SIGKILL)

    ShutdownFinalizing -[#047857]-> StartingModules : <color:#047857>ShutdownFinalizing to StartingModules:</color>\nreload config,\nRestart or Crash under max restarts\n(--recover-module-crashes)

    ShutdownFinalizing -[#047857]-> Idle : <color:#047857>ShutdownFinalizing to Idle:</color>\n(crash cap exceeded with --recover-module-crashes)

    ShutdownFinalizing -[#047857]-> Exiting : <color:#047857>ShutdownFinalizing to Exiting:</color>\nunexpected module exit without --recover-module-crashes

Running -[#3730a3]-> Exiting : <color:#3730a3>Second SIGINT/SIGTERM</color>\n(sigint_received_ already true)\ndirect to Exiting, not via drain

note bottom of G_BOOT
  If shutdown already started,
  the last MQTT ready skips transitioning to Running.
  First SIGINT/SIGTERM while there are no module child PIDs
  (handle_signal): cleanup and go straight to Exiting—no drain.
end note

note bottom of G_DRAIN
  Crash path briefly enters ShutdownRequested,
  then CrashShutdownInProgress.
  ForceTerminating terminates children, and when all children are gone, 
  advances to ShutdownFinalizing.
end note

note top of G_END
  Second SIGINT/SIGTERM: handle_signal goes straight to Exiting
  (no ShutdownRequested / drain path). Process exit code is EXIT_FAILURE.
  Applies from whatever ManagerState you are in; arrow from Running
  is one example (stroke uses Running fill like other edges from Running).
  See manager.cpp handle_signal after sigint_received_ is already true.
end note

legend bottom
  <b>How to read this diagram:</b>
  * <b>Arrow color</b> = fill color of the state where the arrow starts (same # as on that state in the diagram).
  * <b>First line of each label</b> uses the same color as the arrow; following lines use default text color.
  --
  <b>State machine overview:</b>
  * <color:#6366f1><b>Startup</b></color>: from process start until every module is running.
  * <color:#d97706><b>Shutdown / drain</b></color>: stopping module processes (signals, timers, waitpid).
  * <color:#059669><b>Finalize</b></color>: all module children gone; exit vs idle vs reload (see manager.hpp).
  * <color:#0f172a><b>ShutdownCause</b></color> (enum in code): why the drain started—Normal, Crash, or Restart. It is kept across some states so handle_finalize_shutdown_transition can pick the right outcome.
  * <color:#d97706><b>All module PIDs gone</b></color> Transition into ShutdownFinalizing when all module PIDs are gone. That covers ShutdownRequested, CrashShutdownInProgress, RestartRequested, and ForceTerminating.
  * <color:#9a3412><b>Shutdown timeout</b></color> (handle_shutdown_timeout): from ShutdownRequested, CrashShutdownInProgress, or RestartRequested only—if SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT_MS elapses, transition to 
  ForceTerminating, SIGTERM to remaining module children, then SIGKILL after FORCE_KILL_GRACE_TIMEOUT_MS if needed. When handles are finally empty, the same 
  advance_lifecycle_state_if_ready path enters ShutdownFinalizing; ShutdownCause still drives the finish branch.
endlegend

@enduml
